206	#RecommenderArticlesAwaitingRecommendationText:InMyFields	default	<font style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.2em;font-family:Optima;">\r\nThis is the list of all preprints for which no recommender of the community has yet agreed to handle the reviewing and recommendation process.  \r\nYou can pick any articles you wish to recommend (even if you are not suggested as a recommender).  \r\nIn case of any problems or difficulties, please contact us at: [%(contact)s](mailto:%(contact)s)\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n************  \r\n</font>
159	#EthicsInfo	default	<font style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.35em;font-family:Optima;">\r\n\r\n###<div style="text-align:left">Recommenders and reviewers for  %(description)s (%(longname)s) must agree to comply with the following rules:   \r\n  \r\n1.\t<div style="text-align:left">Recommenders for %(longname)s and reviewers should have no financial conflict of interest relating to the articles they evaluate.\r\n\r\n2.\t<div style="text-align:left">Recommenders for %(longname)s and reviewers should have as little non-financial conflict of interest as possible relating to the articles they evaluate, although a complete absence of conflict of interest may be difficult to achieve due to the scientific interest in the subject required. For instance, recommenders for %(longname)s and reviewers should not evaluate articles written by close colleagues and coworkers (people with whom they have published in the last four years, with whom they have received joint funding in the last four years, or with whom they are currently writing a manuscript, or submitting a grant proposal), or written by family members, friends, or anyone for whom bias might affect the nature of their recommendation.\r\n\r\n3.\t<div style="text-align:left">Reviews, recommendations, comments and messages should always be respectful to the authors.\r\n\r\n4.\t<div style="text-align:left">Reviews and recommendations should be of high quality. Reviews should be sufficiently deep and detailed for the %(longname)s recommender handling the recommendation process to gain a full appreciation of the qualities, defects and limitations of the article. Texts (reviews, recommendations, comments, messages to authors) will be returned to %(longname)s recommenders and reviewers if they do not respect these rules.\r\n\r\n5.\t<div style="text-align:left">Recommenders for %(longname)s and reviewers must ensure that the data for recommended preprints are available to readers, through deposition in an open data repository, such as Zenodo, Dryad or institutional repositories, for example. Deposited data must have a digital object identifier (DOI). Recommenders and reviewers must also check that details of the quantitative analyses (e.g. data treatment and statistical scripts in R, bioinformatic pipelines scripts, etc.) in the recommended preprints are available to the readers, as appendices or supplementary online materials (in this case, the supplementary material must have a digital object identifier (DOI)), for example.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Managing Board of %(longname)s has the right to exclude recommenders from %(longname)s if they do not respect these rules.\r\n\r\n</font>
160	#NewRecommendationInfo	default	<font style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.2em;font-family:optima">\r\n##<font color="#598398">Recommend a postprint</font>\r\n**********\r\n####<div style="text-align:left">You are about to recommend a postprint, i.e. an article that has already been peer-reviewed and published in a scientific journal. You must consider that this postprint has strong qualities: crucial, original or previously untested hypotheses, scientific rigor, refinement of the demonstration, outstanding quality of the data and methodology, noteworthy scientific consequences, etc. </div>\r\n####<div style="text-align:left">To recommend a postprint, you need to write a “recommendation” text cosigned with another %(longname)s recommender which will be published by %(longname)s under the license CC-BY-ND. You will be able to write your recommendation text and to declare the co-recommender in the next steps of the process.</div>\r\n####<div style="text-align:left">The "recommendation" text is an article, similar to a News & Views piece, describing the context of the study and explaining why the postprint is particularly interesting to the recommender. It displays its own title, contains between about 300 and 1500 words and references (at least that of the postprint), has a DOI, and is citable.</div>\r\n####<div style="text-align:left">Details about the recommendation process can be found [here](../about/help_generic#Postprint recommendation process)</div>  \r\n&nbsp;\r\n</font>
202	#RecommenderMyRecommendationsPostprintText	default	<font style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.2em;font-family:Optima;">\r\nThis page lists the postprints you have decided to recommend    \r\nIn case of any problems or difficulties, please contact us at: [%(contact)s](mailto:%(contact)s)\r\n************\r\n</font>
313	#CiteInfo	default	<font style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5em;font-family:Optima;text-align:left">\r\n#<font color="#598398">How should you cite a recommended article?</font>  \r\n****************\r\nWhen an article (a preprint or a postprint) is recommended by %(longname)s, you can cite it in your CV and articles as follows:  \r\n\r\n##In your CV  \r\n- Gallet R, Froissart R, Ravigné V. (2017) Things softly attained are long retained: Dissecting the Impacts of Selection Regimes on Polymorphism Maintenance in Experimental Spatially Heterogeneous Environments. *biorXiv*, 100743. Recommended by *Peer Community In Evolutionary Biology*.  [doi: http://dx.doi.org/10.24072/pci.evolbiol.100020](doi: http://dx.doi.org/10.24072/pci.evolbiol.100020)\r\n\r\n##In your manuscripts  \r\n\r\n###In the main text of the manuscript  \r\n- " (Gallet et al. 2017, recommended by Bedhomme 2017) "\r\n\r\n###In the references of the manuscript  \r\n- Gallet R, Froissart R, Ravigné V. (2017) Things softly attained are long retained: Dissecting the Impacts of Selection Regimes on Polymorphism Maintenance in Experimental Spatially Heterogeneous Environments. *biorXiv*, 100743. \r\n- Bedhomme S (2017) Experimental test of the conditions of maintenance of polymorphism under hard and soft selection. *Peer Community in Evolutionary Biology*, 100020. [doi: http://dx.doi.org/10.24072/pci.evolbiol.100020](doi: http://dx.doi.org/10.24072/pci.evolbiol.100020)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n#<font color="#598398">How should you cite a recommendation?</font>\r\n****************\r\nEach recommendation (of a preprint or a postprint) by %(longname)s has a DOI and can therefore be cited as follows (in your CV and manuscripts):  \r\n    \r\n- Bedhomme S (2017) Experimental test of the conditions of maintenance of polymorphism under hard and soft selection. *Peer Community in Evolutionary Biology*, 100020. [doi: http://dx.doi.org/10.24072/pci.evolbiol.100020](doi: http://dx.doi.org/10.24072/pci.evolbiol.100020)\r\n\r\n</font>
201	#PublicRecommendationBoardText	default	<font style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.2em;font-family:optima">\r\n<div style="text-align:left">A recommender manages preprint evaluation. His/her role is very similar to that of a journal editor (handling preprints, finding reviewers, collecting reviews, editorial decisions based on reviews), with the preprint eventually being recommended (or not) after several rounds of reviews. %(longname)s recommenders can recommend up to five preprints or postprints per year. They are expected to comply with the code of ethical conduct of %(longname)s, are eligible for selection as a member of the Managing Board for a period of two years, and can propose the nomination of new recommenders to the Managing Board.</div>  \r\n&nbsp;\r\n</font>
